Just thought I'd give you some information about T-shirt size prints. Not sure at all how either company works, so keep that in mind. I have worked for a screen printing company for over 35 years. We use plastisol inks not water based inks. You have to have a screen for every color on your shirt. If it has 6 colors, then that is 6 screens. It takes time to set up all the screens and get them lined up with each other, the inks put in them and then print the shirts. If you have a dozen shirts say from size small to XXL  you will only get a design that is big enough to fit on the smallest size. That will go on ALL the shirts. They will not be 2, 3 or 4 sizes. Where I work we print small jobs and big jobs. We charge $20 per screen as a one time charge. Six screens cost you $120 and you haven't even bought a blank shirt. That doesn't include printing cost either. After that it's just shirt and printing cost. We usually will made two sets of screens (if the customer will pay) for say youth shirts  (smaller size) and a bigger size for adults. However like I said the small adult through XXL will ALL get the same size adult design and you can only make it as big as will fit on the adult small shirt. Hope this helps with how things are done. I have no idea how Teesprings or Printful work, and if you order 1 shirt at a time you can size it any way you want. However if you order say a dozen they may just size the art as big as they can for the smallest size so they can print them all at once with one set of screens.

No orders, as I am not about to advertise or market  the cup.  Later discovered tons of complaints against Teespring at Better Business Bureau site.  Judging by the complaints, it would have been a risk that they would not have been able to produce my design well.  Also, I ordered a t-shirt from a top YouTube commentator who uses Teespring.  Very long delivery period.  Tracking only goes as far as delivery to the country.  That happened almost ten days ago, but still no delivery and no ability to get in touch with anybody.  Long time to wait around for a delivery.  Also, if I had gone ahead and used them, the slow delivery, with no human contact, would have been a real problem for customers.  So Teespring is off my list.  In fact, I am beginning to think it is better to do my own shipping -- for now anyway, using a printing company whose CEO reaches out in its marketing, and that appears to pride itself on having actual people to deal with its customers.

You could say, there was no sign of peeling or cracking, I'll wash the shirt and check for that. How many washes until fading? White underlayer bleeding out. Color reproduction to submitted file etc.

Packaging is also important to discuss but 1hr after the customer had their product and it's top quality, that won't matter. All they will see is their quality product.

Actually, this comparison is not a comparison at all: Printify does not print the products, it was My Lockers that made the print. And My Lockers use the DIFFERENT printing maschine than Printful. Printful uses Kornit. My Lockers uses some other tgat I do not remember (Brothers-maschines maybe)

Also, the materials are different.

The real message here is only, that Printful with BC succeeded, but printing on NL3600 with those naschines MyLocker uses, is not a good idea.

This DOES NOT mean that Printify or My Lockers are bad companies. It is only a question of the materials and what materials the printing maschines they use, are suitable for each product.

I‘d like to see My Lockers printing on Bella&Canvas 3001, then you can make a real comparison.

That needs morer reseaech, trials and errors. This is also why you cannot put very low profits to your products. When you do the research properly, it takes time and money from you. The result does not rain from the heaven for free.

Thank you!

I add some points here. I have recently made research and compared Printify and Printful and what they offer. I haven‘t ordered any samples yet, so I am happy about this video, because my choise had turned to be Printful despite of the higher price. Anyhow I think I‘ll be use Printify for other products than t-shirts.

I did not study only Printify, but all the printing companies they offer. Why I was not enthusiastic about My Locker is, that they use printing naschines that I do not know so well. But for example DTG2Go in Printify uses Kornit-printing maschines, the same as Printful.

The type of the printing-maschine is important because when making a design, you (a designer) must adjust the colors according to the printing maschine. Colors do not look necessarily the same with the same adjustments if you print with Kornit or some other maschine. I have experience with this when I worked as an architect and made digital plans. I used amount of times to adjust the colors so that they looked nice when they were printed exactly in one printing company and exactly with the one special maschine they had there. Then, one day they said it had got broken... I had to start again!

So, first it is important that you know what adjustments the certain maschine the company you use, demands from a print file.

I chose Printful because they have more color options in BC than DRG2Go. After all the price that I have to pay does not differ a lot, when you really start to calculate ALL expences you must pay. Printful has reasonable shipping prices. Besides, I appreciate the help and support I’ve got from them.

If you put your profits very low, you get nothing from your hard work because after all you must pay taxes and all sort of expences when you keep your shop going on. You need a bookkeeper, the programm, internet costs, adds, graphic designers... you must pay for everything, and if you do not put the profit high enough, soon you notice that YOU are in the zero, and actually giving out more money than getting it. If it is ok to you, then, put very low prices on your shirts. Customers might be happy but you won‘t. The more they buy, the more then you must pay... without profits. Look carefully all expenses you must pay when you plan the price. There are plenty of them.

Propaply and most likely Printful adds the t-shirt prices the costs of this support they can give to the customers, and at this point I am ready to pay for it in the products I use. They also keep a very goof blog. In my opinion it is helpful when starting this business.

Maybe when I have more experience I can change. But now I go on with what I feel is the best.

PC Users please don't take a photo of the screen! :) Here are alternatives
1. Click on the blank spot on the screen
2. CTRL-A (select all)
3. CTRL-C (copy)
4. Paste into MSWord, Open Office, for a close replica or even try notepad though it might be too messy
OR
Just copy paste the lines you care about into notepad or word
OR
PC keyboards have a built in screenshot key, but it's not something everyone knows about. It says PrtScrn. Hitting it will copy the entire screen to the clipboard.
ALT-PrtScrn will just copy what you can see in the current window.
Open MSPaint or Photoshop or whatever and from the edit menu select "Paste" or "Paste into new image"

I need to point something out here that is very misleading and everyone here needs to understand. Reviews for items on ETSY are not accurate the way you describe them. The reviews you see before clicking on an item are for the ENTIRE STORE. Once you click on the item, scroll down and you will see the ACTUAL number of reviews for that specific item. So what you think has over 1k reviews, might only actually have 7 and the high star ratings might not even be for that item. Just FYI.

The only thing is, yes, your unique designs are automatically under copyright -- technically. But if you don't actually copyright them yourself and pay the fee, and if you wind up in court charging someone with copyright infringement, the automatic copyright won't be enough. Because it's not dated. In a lawsuit, it's always the one with the earliest date (or any date) wins.

You CAN print their screen on a PC - but multiple saves don't work: the most recent save always over-writes the previous. So what has to be done is open an image editing program like Photoshop first, then go to the video on the PC from which screen shots are to be taken and, when you get to a screen you want to save, pause the program and tap the "PrtSc / SysRq" key (upper right of most keyboards). After that, go immediately to your graphic program and open a new, blank document. The size of the document should automatically come up preset to the pixel size of your computer screen (at whatever resolution has been set). That's the way it works in Photoshop, but you may have to set the resolution manually in a different program. Make sure it's exact. Lastly, select 'Paste' and the screen shot will be imported to your blank document. Save your document, then, leaving the graphic program up and ready, return to the video and go to the next place you want to save a screenshot, and repeat the process.

FYI: The review-count/rating on Etsy isn't the rating for a specific design. It's the rating for the shop/seller/designer. Means: the review-count doesn't say anything about how well a specific design has been sold and rated. If you have a big shop that sells hunderts or thousends of diffrent articles on Etsy, the real sellcount on a specific design is logically much lower than its sellers overall-rating. anyways, the rating tells you at least, if a design comes from a successful seller. And if you visit the sellers page, you get an insight of single reviews and to which article they relate (like on amazons multi-article-pages).

I failed to study this business. It didn't screw me. Other artist and entrepreneurs didn't screw me. Well, that's not entirely true. A Chinese nationalist on "Etsy," told the company I was stealing his designs and they fired me. LOL... Yeah, each and every one of my 97 designs were his. 97 designs that were all hand painted on 16X20 cloth canvases were his. Did he destroy my business? Yes! That bastard..... Nope, he didn't. I never, not once, sold a single piece of clothing on Etsy. His lies hurt my little feelings for a few days. My wife said it was months, but, she lies too. But, all in all, it is my fault I cannot afford the advertising...and my fault for not knowing advertising played such a huge part. I can blame no one for my failure other than myself, although, I can thank that same person for not quitting.

Hey Biaheza, great video as usual.

I notice that most people always display a high ”was” price crossed out alongside a much more realistic ”now” or ”sale” price against their products. I have two questions on this approach:

Firstly, is it legal to do that kind of thing from the outset? I believe in some countries you are required to have had the original, unreduced price in circulation for a certain time period before you can then reduce it and show it as ”now” or ”sale”.

Secondly, does such a tactic really work? I’m sure it would in the US, but what about in other markets? I am British and as a nation we are very suspicious of things that seem to good to be true, and seeing fairly mediocre looking products advertised as ”Was €99 Now €9.99” would send most people running unleat the products are in the ”Sale” or ”Bargain Basement” section. It’s pretty much the same in Germany where I now live, where sensationalism is frowned upon meaning such a marketing strategy is unlikely to work so well here. Thoughts?

I feel like I have reviewed so many of these get rich quick schemes. They all sound so good at the beginning, then you find out all they are trying to do is help get the guy in the ad even richer by you doing work for them to promote their site or product or they want to sell you an education on how to get rich quick. However, there are companies out there (smaller ones) that just need your help marketing their product and getting it out there and they pay a commission to you if someone buys their product because you did the leg work. You can do this via social media, youtube, etc. It costs you nothing but time, and it will not get you rich quick.

Helpful tips

You search instagram by niche. Research the associated pages
Then you DM!
You can build up presence by posting, liking, sharing and replying to questions in comment sections. It's an additional way to divert traffic via influencer markets in your niche.
Most pages rely on DMs regarding marketing a product in order to earn a salary. They are also running a business. Send a bunch of template messages out but make sure you don't include product info in initial message and make sure it's not super spammy.
I find that negotiating at the start gives you an idea of the influencer for potential future marketing services. The more information you get at the start of your working relationships the more you can record that data to build a better and more sustainable business long term. Also advise all your influencers that you do business with to let you know personally/directly when they are running special offers/discounts. Not only does this get you money off but it also gives you an idea of the finances or lifestyle of the influencer.
Some burn through money at a high rate relying on promoting themselves and the services they offer In order to replenish their funds. For the cut throats in business this is opportunity staring you In the face. Negotiate a deal that works for your business in the long term. Maybe a bigger cash upfront offer for a block of slots over the next week/month or specific dates each month. Tailor make your ad campaigns around your data.
I recommend when starting out you have a back up cash pot of at least a grand so you can be comfortable with allowing the site to grow organically. Follow a strict routine of self promotion via social media and all other effective sources. The back up cash pot is for your own living expenses so your not desperate for cash. The less you need money in a hurry the clearer your mind will be. Your better to use your slow period to learn more about the industry via YouTube or a course you have trust in. With dropshipping it's important to have a routine that you can enjoy so you have contrast in your lifestyle. A nice setting to get working on the laptop processing orders. Long lunch breaks with quality food and good company. Take a tech free hour each day at a set time. Lock it all away and just walk or meditate. You will look forward to these moments and they will help build the bigger picture of your career path. Eventually put your ROI back into the business but pay yourself a weekly percentage dividend so you see extra funds becoming accessible each week. It helps the mind focus on increasing the digits on the deposits rather than stressing that no money is being paid but money is going out for ads etc.
Once you have big profits real estate is your safest bet right now. Get at least 2 properties within the next 5 years and you should be set for life in terms of comfort and survivability. Then you can reach for the stars once your stable for life and earn your fortune to leave behind for the family.
Hope this helps

Most people don't realize the amount of effort that goes toward creating something like this. This method is not a get rich quick method. Anyone getting into e-commerce should be prepared to dedicate A LOT of time into learning and practicing, as well as resources for starting your store(s) and testing various advertisements and campaigns until they find their winners. If you are getting started in e-commerce the best recommendation I can give you is to be prepared to allocate a certain number of hours a week to learning and creating your niche store or funnel, and to have INCOME! You can't start e-commerce without disposable income, whether that be $50-100 dollars a week, or a couple thousand. You need to have income so that you can afford to test and take chances until you have mastered your skills and niche. I've been doing this for 2 years now and just now am I starting to develop the key skills to get this going. I wish someone told me all this before getting started because it can be really frustrating to create a store and spend money on advertisements only to see no returns. Don't get bummed out, it will take time and a whole lot of failures, but with hard work and dedication you got this! Stay hungry, stay humble, and stay laser focused!

Wow wow wow, your content is substantial, I can’t believe it’s free! You really dig into things thoroughly and draw it out in a way that we can really go through the steps along your journey piece by piece and place ourselves there, which helps immensely. And what’s most magical about your content is that you take something that can seem colossal & overwhelming, and you break it down into digestible, doable steps. What I’m really getting from this video is that the journey to where you’re going unfolds progressively as you move along (with patience & refusing to give up!), and we needn’t get stopped by our thoughts of how can we ever reach the mountain-top far off in the distance which seems so unattainable, and so many people do get tripped up by that thinking, and then don’t even begin the process. But you totally demonstrate here just taking the next step in front of you, doing that well and effectively, learning & growing from it, and then repeating what worked and implementing what you learned in the next higher rung in the ladder, and then the next and the next, and you just keep moving along like that, building momentum until you’ve created a sustainable business which becomes more automated with time and doesn’t require as much work to uphold as it did to get it off the ground. It’s great to have an ultimate goal as a vision, but your mind should just be focused on the part of the process that you’re on right now, or you’ll feel overwhelmed and discouraged and end up giving up. It’s like when you’re following directions to a place on google maps — you can have the background intention of ending up at your destination, but you have to keep your full focus on the road that you’re actually on and what is the very next turn coming up, not ten steps ahead in the directions. You’ll always end up lost that way. Thank you for so effectively exemplifying this point. Well done.
